Reads a file.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read.
    filter - The string to filter on (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is found it will return all lines that matched the filter. If no match 
is found, no line are returned.
    iterate - If set to false, only count is returned.  If set to true, then each row will be returned for each subsequent call.
Valid values\: true, false
    delimiter - If set to null, the file is read line by line and each line becomes the returnResult. Otherwise, the delimiter is inserted between each 
line that is read and becomes the returnResult. (note, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size).
    eofReset - If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the 
next call.
    characterSet - CharacterSet of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value \:UTF-8

Responses\:
    success - The operation succesfully read the file (if iterate is true, more rows are available).
    no more items - No more items are available for retrieval.
    failure - The operation failed to read the file.

Extra Results\:
COUNT - The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read.

Writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file,  append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Input Parameters\:
source           -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
contents        - The contents to write to the file. Contents can have a new line delimiter which is also given as input to the operation, but it is optional. Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
delimiter         - Specifies the newline delimiter (\n, \r\n, etc) that is used for the "contents" input.
characterSet  - The character encoding used to write to the file. The default is UTF-8. Example values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
overwrite       - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. By default, the used value is true. Accepted values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Responses\:
success - file/directory is written successfully
failure   - unable to write to file/directory

Generates a file with a unique name.

Inputs\:
prefix - A prefix for the file name.
suffix - A suffix for the filename, if nothing is specified, .tmp will be used.
directory - A directory to hold the temp file.

Results\:
